George Bush: Nomination of Edith E. Holiday To Be General Counsel of the Department of the Treasury












Tweet









Nomination of Edith E. Holiday To Be General Counsel of the Department of the TreasuryFebruary 2, 1989











George Bush1989: Book I 
Font Size:













Share











The American Presidency ProjectPromote Your Page Too


The President today announced his intention to nominate Edith E. Holiday to be General Counsel for the Department of the Treasury. She would succeed Mark Sullivan III. Since 1988 Ms. Holiday has been an Assistant Secretary (Public Affairs and Public Liaison) of the Department of the Treasury and Counselor to the Secretary. Prior to this she was chief counsel and national financial and operations director for the Bush-Quayle '88 Presidential campaign and served as director of operations for George Bush for President. She was also special counsel for the Fund for America's Future and Executive Director for the Quadrennial Commission on Executive, Legislative, and Judicial Salaries, 1984 - 1985. Ms. Holiday practiced law with the firm of Dow, Lohnes & Albertson, 1983 - 1984 and with the firm of Reed, Smith, Shaw & McClay, 1977 - 1983. She also served as legislative director for then-U.S. Senator Nicholas F. Brady. Ms. Holiday graduated from the University of Florida (B.S., 1974; J.D., 1977). She was born February 14, 1952, in Middletown, OH. She is married to Terrence B. Adamson and currently resides in Atlanta, GA.
Citation: George Bush: "Nomination of Edith E. Holiday To Be General Counsel of the Department of the Treasury," February 2, 1989. Online by Gerhard Peters and John T. Woolley, The American Presidency Project. http://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/ws/?pid=16641.










Home         
			 




© 1999-2017 - Gerhard Peters and John T. Woolley - The American Presidency Project ™







 





EDITH E. HOLIDAY, A LAYWER, WEDS Edith E. Holiday, a lawyer and the executive director of the Commission on Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries in Washington, and Terrence B. Adamson, a lawyer, were married yesterday in Washington. The Rev. Terence L. Elsberry performed the ceremony at St. John's Episcopal Church on Lafayette Square.   Nancy Stroup Holland was matron of honor for her cousin. Terrence Morgan Adamson, the bridegroom's 14-year-old son by a previous marriage that ended in divorce, was best man.   The bride, who will retain her name, is the daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Harry Holiday Jr. of Middletown, Ohio. A graduate of the University of Florida, where she also received a law degree, she is on leave from the Washington and Atlanta law firm of Dow, Lohnes & Albertson to head the commission, a Federal agency whose nine members are named by the three branches of Government. Her father is chairman and former chief executive officer of Armco Inc.   Mr. Adamson, the son of Mr. and Mrs. S. B. Adamson of Calhoun, Ga., graduated from Emory University and its law school. From 1977 to 1979 he was an assistant to Attorney General Griffin B. Bell and the chief spokesman for the Department of Justice. Mr. Adamson is now a managing partner in the law firm of Hansell & Post in Atlanta. His parents, who are retired, owned a dry-cleaning concern. - NYTimes.com




























































