EDITH E. HOLIDAY, A LAYWER, WEDS Edith E. Holiday, a lawyer and the executive director of the Commission on Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries in Washington, and Terrence B. Adamson, a lawyer, were married yesterday in Washington. The Rev. Terence L. Elsberry performed the ceremony at St. John's Episcopal Church on Lafayette Square.   Nancy Stroup Holland was matron of honor for her cousin. Terrence Morgan Adamson, the bridegroom's 14-year-old son by a previous marriage that ended in divorce, was best man.   The bride, who will retain her name, is the daughter of Mr. and Mrs. Harry Holiday Jr. of Middletown, Ohio. A graduate of the University of Florida, where she also received a law degree, she is on leave from the Washington and Atlanta law firm of Dow, Lohnes & Albertson to head the commission, a Federal agency whose nine members are named by the three branches of Government. Her father is chairman and former chief executive officer of Armco Inc.   Mr. Adamson, the son of Mr. and Mrs. S. B. Adamson of Calhoun, Ga., graduated from Emory University and its law school. From 1977 to 1979 he was an assistant to Attorney General Griffin B. Bell and the chief spokesman for the Department of Justice. Mr. Adamson is now a managing partner in the law firm of Hansell & Post in Atlanta. His parents, who are retired, owned a dry-cleaning concern.
Published: June 9, 1985









